Geostatistical Modeling with SPDE-R-INLA

Osafu Egbon

2025-05-22

Given

\[ Y(s) = \mathbf{X}(s)^\top \boldsymbol{\beta} + \varepsilon(s) \quad \text{with } \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \text{~} N(\mathbf{0}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}) \]

Lets simulate he response \(Y\).

set.seed(12543)
library(INLA)

# Filter for Nigeria

# Generate points uniformly inside the Nigeria polygon

set.seed(42)  # for reproducibility

# Set number of points
n <- 1000

points_nigeria <- st_sample(nigeria, size = n, type = "random")


# Filter for Nigeria
nigeria <- subset(world, admin == "Nigeria")

# Filter for Nigeria

ggplot(data = world) +
  geom_sf(fill = "antiquewhite", color = "gray") +
  geom_sf(data = points_nigeria, color = "black", size =.5, alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_sf(data = nigeria, fill = NA, color = "black", size = 1.2) +
  coord_sf(xlim = c(-10, 20), ylim = c(-10, 20), expand = FALSE) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Map of Nigeria in Global Context",
       caption = "Data: Natural Earth")

#### Get sample locations for modeling

locs <- st_coordinates(points_nigeria)

# 2. Define the SPDE model to simulate from
mesh <- inla.mesh.2d(loc = locs, max.edge = c(2, 3), cutoff = 0.01)

### PLot mesh 

plot(mesh)
points(locs,col="blue",cex = 0.2,pch=19)

#### Get SPDE model 

spde <- inla.spde2.matern(mesh, alpha = 2)

# 3. Simulate latent spatial field
Q <- inla.spde2.precision(spde, theta = c(log(1), log(0.2)))  #sigma=1, range ~ 0.2

x <- inla.qsample(n = 1, Q = Q)  # one realization

# 4. Project spatial field to locations
A <- inla.spde.make.A(mesh, loc = locs)
spatial_field <- as.vector(A %*% x)

The spatial error \(\varepsilon(s)\) is “spatial_field”.

Now simulate the covariate.

# 5. Add fixed effects and simulate data
beta0 <- 1.5
beta1 <- 2.5
beta2 <- -1.4
beta = matrix(c(beta0,beta1,beta2))

X = cbind(x0 =1,x1 = rnorm(n,1,.1), x2 = rnorm(n,0,.1))

Let \(\eta = \mathbf{X}(s)^\top \boldsymbol{\beta} +\varepsilon(s)\)

eta <- X%*%beta + spatial_field

Y <- rnorm(n, mean = eta, sd = 0.2)


# Compare true vs predicted
df_plot <- data.frame(
  long = locs[,1],
  lat = locs[,2],
  Expected = eta,
  x0= X[,1],
    x1= X[,2],
    x2= X[,3],
  Obs = Y
)

#### Plot observed response on a map

p1 = ggplot(df_plot, aes(x = long, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Obs), size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Observed", color = "Observed respose") +

    colours = c("#440154FF", "#31688EFF", "#35B779FF", "#FDE725FF"),
    name = "Expression"

# Fitting SPDE model

# 1. Stack for INLA
stk <- inla.stack(
  data = list(y = Y), # Response variable
  A = list(1, A,1, 1),     # Projection Matrix
  effects = list(
    Intercept = rep(1, n), # Intercept
    spatial = 1:spde$n.spde,
   # x0= X[,1],
    x1= X[,2],
    x2= X[,3]
  ),
  tag = "est"
)

# 2. Fit the model
formula <- y ~ 0 + Intercept + x1+x2+ f(spatial, model = spde)
result <- inla(
  formula,
  data = inla.stack.data(stk),
  control.predictor = list(A = inla.stack.A(stk), compute = TRUE),
  control.compute = list(dic = TRUE, cpo = TRUE)
)

summary(result)

# Visualizing result

library(ggplot2)

# Extract fitted spatial field
index_spatial <- inla.stack.index(stk, tag = "est")$data
eta_post_mean <- result$summary.linear.predictor$mean[index_spatial]

# Compare true vs predicted
df_plot <- data.frame(
  long = locs[,1],
  lat= locs[,2],
  true = eta,
  fitted = eta_post_mean

# 3. Predict over a grid of new locations



grid <- st_make_grid(nigeria, cellsize = 0.1, what = "centers") 

# Keep only points within the Nigeria boundary
grid_within <- grid[st_within(grid, nigeria, sparse = FALSE)]

grid <- st_coordinates( grid_within )
 
A_pred <- inla.spde.make.A(mesh = mesh, loc = as.matrix(grid))

stk_pred <- inla.stack(
  data = list(y = NA),
  A = list(1, A_pred),
  effects = list(
    Intercept = rep(1, nrow(grid)),
    spatial = 1:spde$n.spde
  ),
  tag = "pred"
)

# Combine estimation and prediction stacks
stk_full <- inla.stack(stk, stk_pred)

# 4. Fit the model with full stack
result <- inla(
  formula,
  data = inla.stack.data(stk_full),
  control.predictor = list(
    A = inla.stack.A(stk_full),
    compute = TRUE
  ),
  control.compute = list(dic = TRUE)
)

# 5. Extract predictions at grid locations
index_pred <- inla.stack.index(stk_full, tag = "pred")$data
pred_mean <- result$summary.linear.predictor$mean[index_pred]

# 6. Visualize predictions
df_pred <- data.frame(
 long = grid[,"X"],
  lat = grid[,"Y"],
  pred = pred_mean
)

p3 = ggplot(df_pred, aes(x = long, y = lat, fill = pred)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  labs(title = "Predicted Spatial Surface (Posterior Mean)", fill = "Prediction") +
  theme_minimal()
